Elon Musk has been forced to step down as Tesla's chairman.
The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission and Tesla founder Elon Musk have settled their fraud dispute.
This is reported by CNBC News.
According to the network, Musk will have to step down as chairman of Tesla's board of directors.
The commission allowed Musk to keep his position as Tesla's CEO.
The company's founder will also have to pay a $20 million administrative fine.
The same amount will be charged to Tesla.
The money will be distributed among the affected investors.
In addition, the company must appoint two independent directors.
Elon Musk is an American businessman who is listed as one of the 50 richest people on the planet by Forbes magazine.
He is the head of the space corporation SpaceX, the neurotechnology company Neuralink and the developer of the Tesla electric car, as well as the co-founder of Paypal.
The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission has previously sued Tesla CEO Elon Musk over a tweet about a possible buyout.
Last month, Musk announced plans to take Tesla private and buy back all of its stock at a fixed price of $420.
The $420 price tag was set allegedly "due to the significance of the number in marijuana culture", Bloomberg reported earlier, citing the commission's co-director of security Steven Peakin.
However, Elon Musk later abandoned his plans to buy back the shares.
Commenting on the lawsuit filed against him by the US Securities and Exchange Commission, the businessman said he considered the fraud allegations unfounded, and added that he was very disappointed and saddened by these claims.
"Honesty is the most important value in my life, and the facts will prove that I have not violated it in any way", the businessman said in an interview with CNBC.
In August, a group of Tesla shareholders filed a class action lawsuit against Musk, complaining of financial losses.
The plaintiffs claimed that the businessman's posts had caused them a loss.
In particular, one shareholder claimed that the businessman's tweets were misleading, forcing Tesla stock sellers to buy securities at artificially inflated prices to cover their positions.
Other plaintiffs also noted that Musk's careless statements led to sharp fluctuations in the exchange rate.
In September, Elon Musk was accused of stock market fraud by the head of the research company Citron Research.
Meanwhile, if Musk failed to settle his dispute with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, he could face suspension from the company's board and even jail.
This was stated by former chairman of the commission Harvey Pitt to CNBC.
Musk is "a good guy who can't run a car company".
