On September 30, 1928, exactly 90 years ago, the British bacteriologist Alexander Fleming announced his unprecedented discovery.
The discovery of penicillin ushered in the era of modern antibiotics, brought Fleming worldwide fame, and made him a Nobel laureate.
By the way, the extraction of penicillin from mold was not Fleming's first discovery.
A few years earlier, he had a cold and sowed mucus from his own nose on a Petri dish - a glass lid used for testing bacteria - and found that the bacteria had been destroyed a few days later.
And penicillin was discovered by almost the same accident.
Fleming's name was included in the list of the 100 most outstanding people in human history.
His discovery, many scientists say, changed the course of history.
With penicillin, medicine began to cope with most of the oldest diseases that had been considered incurable - tuberculosis, syphilis, gangrene.
When Fleming arrived in the French capital in 1945, shortly after receiving the Nobel Prize, the Paris newspapers reported: "He has done more than a dozen divisions to defeat fascism and liberate France".
Experts estimate that Fleming's discovery of the world's first antibiotic saved the lives of more than 200 million people.
Alexander Fleming died at his home in London in 1955 of a heart attack.
He was cremated, and a week later his ashes were buried in London's famous St. Paul's Cathedral.
