The head of the Federation Council Committee on International Affairs Konstantin Kosachev considers the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly successful for Russia and does not rule out that it could be a turning point in the perception of Russia as an integral participant in the solution of global world problems.
"The uniqueness of this 73rd session, in my opinion, is that the rhetoric we have become almost accustomed to in recent years in relation to Russia has now been much more muted", the senator said in an interview published Sunday in the "Rossiyskaya Gazeta".
He explained that in previous years Russia was sometimes "marked as one of the three main threats to humanity, along with Ebola, climate change or terrorism, Russia was in this category, at least in the presentation of a group of Western countries, which was quite unanimous on this matter".
At the 73rd session, Kosachev stressed, "the topic of Russia in a negative sense was almost absent".
"If you carefully analyze the speech of the president of the United States, the president of France, the speech of the German foreign minister, I am not taking Ukraine, Georgia, or the British, at least the chorus was not quite accurate", the politician noted, noting that Russia "was no longer a wall that is trained with tennis balls".
The head of the Federation Council's relevant committee does not rule out that this indicates a trend that, in his opinion, "will be the highlight of the current session [of the UN General Assembly], although this trend may be fully manifested in a year, two, three".
"I do not exclude that this session in some sense may be a turning point", Kosachev admitted, explaining that "there are too many examples of how Russia's involvement can move forward in international affairs".
He gave examples of the situation in Syria, around Iran and North Korea.
"Unfortunately, it is not Ukraine yet, but I have no doubt that the Russian vision of the Ukrainian crisis will also be in demand over time", the MP added.
This is due to the fact, he believes, that there is an "adequate, healthy perception of Russia as not just possible - an integral participant in solving the global problems of our time".
"I don't want to be wrong, but I have a feeling that we are at a point where moving forward is not going backwards", he added.
Another "interesting and important feeling" in this context, Kosachev called "a request for a Russian vision of how the modern world should develop".
"I have attended many meetings of the head of the Russian delegation [at the session of the General Assembly] of the Minister of Foreign Affairs Sergey Lavrov, I have held my own meetings, and I was very pleased to see that if a year or two or five years ago the Russian opinion, the Russian vision of what is happening in the world, by and large, nobody was interested, then now the situation is different", - said the Chairman of the Committee of the Council of Federation.
He believes this is because "the so-called new liberal order, which is personified by the West, has no answers to the questions of how to solve world problems due to the obvious shortage of ideas in the global space, the shortage of ideas on how to solve the problems of the Middle East, the problems of terrorism, the problems of non-proliferation of nuclear weapons, the problems of migration".
"And here the request for a Russian vision is becoming more and more obvious", Kosachev said, stressing that he considers the current session "successful for the work of the Russian delegation, successful for Russia".
