The A.D.G. is the second most popular in Germany
The anti-immigrant Alternative for Germany is breaking another popularity record, and Angela Merkel's ratings are falling.
It seems that the German people have become seriously tired of Angela Merkel's immigration policies, which have made the country a coveted destination for millions of refugees from the Middle East.
The latest opinion polls show that the anti-immigrant Alternative for Germany party is gaining popularity and that the positions of Merkel and Seehofer's ruling bloc are weakening.
This week, the ADG broke another record, rising to second place in the popularity ranking.
The right-wing conservatives, with 17 percent of the popularity, managed to overtake the social democrats, who have about 16 percent.
The one-percent gap can be attributed to statistical errors, but it is also worth noting that the ADG, which was founded in 2013 by a small group of eurosceptic economists, has grown into a major political force.
The leadership in the general election is still held by the ruling bloc of the CSU/CDU, which has about 30 percent.
However, there is a trend towards a loss of points - back in April, the support of Angela Merkel's bloc was four percentage points higher.
The personal rating of the German chancellor, who is heading the German government for the fourth consecutive term, is also falling.
Today, 48 percent of Germans support Angela Merkel, down 7 percent from last year.
The Social Democrats are followed by the Greens (15%), the Left (11%) and the Liberals (10%).
The evolution of the Alternatives
The Alternative for Germany party was founded in September 2012 on the basis of the Alternative Choice 2013 group, which included members of the Christian Democratic Union.
The group initially opposed the government's policy, but initially dealt only with economic issues, including the euro and EU cooperation.
The group opposed Germany's "sponsorship" of the weak EU economies, and did not rule out a return to the German mark and a complete exit of the country from the European Union.
The political platform of the AfD has expanded amid the deepening immigration crisis.
In 2013, the group became a full-fledged party that took on a niche of Eurosceptics and began to harshly criticize the government for its failed immigration policies.
At the last parliamentary election in 2017, the AfD managed to make its way into the Bundestag for the first time, winning 94 seats (out of 709).
Two representatives of the Alternative for Germany won seats in the European Parliament.
