The scientist spoke about the possible scientific program of the Russian expedition to the Moon
Head of the Institute of Space Research of the Russian Academy of Sciences, corresponding member of the Russian Academy of Sciences Anatoly Petrukovich told RIA Novosti about a possible program of scientific research for Russian cosmonauts on the Moon.
He said that the scientific community is now working on developing such directions.
"There is no consensus yet", he said.
He noted that one option is to place a low-frequency radio telescope on the far side of the moon, which would avoid interference from the Earth.
"This is the only place where such a telescope can be deployed to study space sources of radio radiation", added Petrukovich.
He also believes the moon could be used to test robotics, to use local resources for construction.
In addition, astronauts should be involved in the search for primitive organisms on the Earth's moon, he says.
It could help us figure out how life arises on planets.
