EU allocates €1.5 million to help victims in Indonesia
The European Union (EU) has allocated €1.5 million to Indonesia to combat the effects of the earthquake and tsunami.
This was reported by the press service of the European Commission on September 30.
The European Commission has sent its experts to the region to monitor the assistance.
The funds will be used for disinfection, as well as food, water, temporary shelter and medicines.
The Commission also gave Indonesian authorities access to satellite maps of the European Copernicus Emergency Service ("Copernicus") to assess the damage.
The United States has also expressed readiness to assist in the response to the disaster, said a statement from State Department spokeswoman Heather Nauert.
It is also reported that the US diplomatic mission in Indonesia has received no reports of American citizens injured.
