Macedonians are preparing to vote in a referendum on joining the EU and NATO if the country changes its name.
The agreement to rename the former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia the Republic of North Macedonia was reached on 17 June as a result of long negotiations with neighboring Greece, which refused to recognize its northern neighbor's right to be called Macedonia, seeing in such a name an attempt on the homonymous Greek province and Greek history.
Ljupko Petkovski, political scientist: "Thanks to this agreement, Macedonia or North Macedonia gets the right to a better future, the hope of social change.
And Greece will assert its right to its past.
There are no perfect agreements.
They are the result of difficult compromises that cannot make absolutely everyone happy".
The ruling Social Democrats led by Prime Minister Zoran Zaev are in favor of renaming the country.
The opposition is the conservative opposition and the president of the country, Georgy Ivanov.
According to journalist Tsvetin Chilimanov, Macedonia has no reason to join the EU - it is enough to have partnership relations with it: "Many of those who do not like the agreement believe that the current socialist government led by Zaev is imposed from outside in order to change the name of the country.
But that decision will have negative consequences.
First of all, the loss of sovereignty.
It is obvious that there are countries that would not want Macedonia to remain one of the sovereign countries in the Balkans".
Faye Dulgeri, Euronews: "The former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia is facing the biggest challenge in its history.
The country is at a crossroads.
The choice made by Macedonian citizens will determine the future not only of the Balkans but of Europe as a whole".
The Russian Ministry of Finance has forecast the ruble for 17 years
The Russian Ministry of Finance expects the ruble to weaken gradually - to 73.9 rubles per dollar by 2031-2035, according to the draft long-term budget forecast, which was submitted to the State Duma together with the federal budget.
In 2021-2025, the ruble exchange rate, according to the forecast, will be 66,4 rubles per dollar, in 2026-2030 - 71,1 rubles, and in the next five years - 73,9.
The Office notes that these figures are nominal.
The real effective exchange rate (a measure that takes into account the change in the currencies of the countries that are the main trading partners of the Russian Federation) will remain stable, officials assure.
As for inflation, it will be 3.5% until 2020, and then stabilize at about 4%, the Ministry of Finance estimates.
