Peskov answered a question about possible support for Serbia in Kosovo
Russian President Dmitry Peskov's spokesman believes it is too early to say whether Russia will help Serbia after the escalation in Kosovo.
He said the first thing to do is to have talks between the leaders of the two countries.
The Kremlin spokesman told reporters at the radio station "Moscow Speaks" on Sunday, September 30.
On September 29, Serbian resident Alexander Vucic announced that he intends to discuss the situation in Kosovo with Russian President Vladimir Putin at a meeting in Moscow on October 2.
The Serbian leader also planned to ask Moscow for support in the situation, specifying that military assistance was not in question.
Vucic noted that he wanted to preserve peace in the region and intends to do everything necessary to do so.
Earlier that day, it was reported that the president of Serbia had ordered the country's armed forces to be brought into a state of maximum combat readiness.
